description.cancellation_policy:
You may cancel your permit at any time and the quota will be released and made available to others interested in acquiring a permit. There is no refund offered with cancellations.  

Changes to your itinerary may be made in advance through “My Reservations” or when picking up your permit, subject to availability. Increasing group size will incur additional fees. It is not possible to change the entry date or the trip leader of a reservation. If you wish to change your entry date or trip leader, you must make a new reservation.
description.comment_box_description: Response Required: In your own words, please describe your intended first night's campsite in greater detail. Please also include any other remarks you have regarding this permit request.
description.description:
A wilderness permit is required year-round for any overnight stay in the Yosemite Wilderness. Permits provide for overnight access to undeveloped areas in the park and involve backpacking a significant distance from a trailhead and all development. Wilderness permits can NOT be used for campgrounds , day hike permits or lodging facilities.

Nearly 95% of Yosemite National Park is congressionally-designated Wilderness. When in the wilderness, every visitor has the responsibility to minimize their impact and practice Leave No Trace. Visit our website to learn more about Yosemite’s Wilderness History.  

In order to minimize human impact and provide visitors with opportunities for solitude, wilderness permits are only issued to a limited number of people for each trailhead each day. Since many trails are very popular, advanced reservations are recommended.
description.driving_directions: There are four entrances into Yosemite National Park that can lead to the five permit issuing stations in the park. You may pick up your permit at any of the five Yosemite Wilderness Permit Stations during open hours, regardless of the preferred permit issuing station listed on your reservation.
description.fee_policy:
Permit fees are non-refundable. There will be no refunds offered once a purchase has been made.

Lottery Fees:

There is a $10 fee to enter a lottery. You may submit one application per group to each seven (7) day lottery window. If your lottery application is successful, you will be charged an additional $5 per person when you confirm your reservation. No part of this fee is refundable. 

Advanced Reservation and Walk-Up Fees:

There is a one time fee of $10 per permit and $5 per person for reservations acquired after the lottery and at the walk-up window. No part of this fee is refundable.
description.lottery_information:
The reservable quota of wilderness permits is first allotted through a weekly lottery, 24 weeks in advance of the entry date. Each group may submit one application to each seven (7) day lottery window. Multiple applications for the same lottery are not allowed.

Applicants may submit up to eight (8) preferred itineraries per application, with only one itinerary being awarded per week. The application period is from Sunday at 12:01 a.m. (PT) to Saturday at 11:59 p.m., with email notification of outcome sent by the following Monday. Successful lottery applicants must confirm their reservation by Thursday at 11:59 p.m. 

Any remaining reservable quota for each lottery window will be released and available for general on sale reservation on Friday at 9:00 a.m.
description.need_to_know_email:
This is not your permit. Please read the following information carefully.

You have reserved a wilderness backpacking permit. This is not a car-camping reservation. For clarification, please contact us immediately at 209-379-0740.

You must pick up your permit in person at any open Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station the day before, or the day of your permit entry date. You must pick up your permit by 11:00 a.m. on your entry date or place it on hold for late pick-up, or it will be cancelled. To place your permit on hold, log in to your recreation.gov account to modify your permit reservation and mark it for late pick-up within one week of your entry date. 

Other things you need to know:

  • Bear-Resistant Food Storage is required for all overnight stays in Yosemite Wilderness. Bear canisters are available for rent at a Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station for $5 per week (deposit required).
  • Check Current Wilderness Conditions for trail conditions and timely updates.
  • More information is available on the Yosemite Backpacking page.
  • Explore Public Transportation Options for going to and getting around Yosemite National Park.
  • Backpackers campgrounds are available for wilderness permit holders to spend one night before and one night after a wilderness trip. Reservations are not required nor necessary. The fee is $8 per person, per night (pay using envelopes at the campground; exact change required). 

To contact us:

  • Preferred: If you have other questions about reservations please fill out this form and we will get back to you within two business days.
  • If you would like to speak to a reservation assistant, call 209-372-0740 (Monday through Friday, 9:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.).
  • If you have general questions about Yosemite Wilderness, call 209-372-0826 (Monday through Friday, 9:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.). This number is generally staffed between April and October.
description.need_to_know_order:
A wilderness permit is required year-round for any overnight stay in the Yosemite Wilderness. A wilderness permit is NOT applicable for campgrounds, day hikes, or for staying in lodging facilities. Changes to your itinerary may be made in advance through “My Reservations” or at a Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station , subject to availability. It is not possible to change your entry date. Increasing group size will incur additional fees. 

  • Permit and lottery fees are non-refundable. Lottery applications must be one person per party traveling together. Duplicate applications will be cancelled without refund.
  • Wilderness camping and travel is subject to wilderness regulations. All trip participants are responsible for knowing and obeying wilderness permit conditions.
  • Itineraries provided are reviewed for compliance with Wilderness regulations. Please pay attention to all communications as you may be required to modify your itinerary in order to comply with regulations. Unfeasible permits may be subject to cancellation if not modified within five (5) days of initial warning. All party members are responsible for following permit conditions; violations may be cited under 36 CFR Part 2.
  • This reservation is not a wilderness permit and cannot be used for overnight travel. Bring this reservation confirmation and proof of identity to pick up your wilderness permit at a Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station. 
  • You must pick up your permit in person during open hours at any Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station the day before, or day of permit entry date by 11:00 a.m. If not picked up by 11:00 a.m. on your entry date, your permit will be cancelled and made available as a walk-up permit. If you cannot pick up your permit by 11:00 a.m. on your entry date, login to your recreation.gov account to modify your permit reservation and mark it for late pick-up. This must be done prior to 11:00 a.m on your entry date and can only be done within one week of your entry date.
description.need_to_know_permit:
A wilderness permit is required year-round for any overnight stay in the Yosemite Wilderness.

Wilderness camping and travel is subject to wilderness regulations . All permit quotas are based on entry date and entry trailhead. All trip participants are responsible for knowing and obeying the conditions of their wilderness permit. If you intend to cross through Yosemite Valley, or walk along Glacier Point and/or Tioga Road at any point during this backpacking trip, you will need an additional wilderness permit to re-enter the wilderness. The maximum stay for a wilderness permit is 14 nights in Yosemite National Park.  

Application Review: Wilderness permit applications will be reviewed by Yosemite Conservancy Wilderness Reservation Staff. Follow your status closely, as you may be required to adapt your itinerary to be in compliance with wilderness regulations or seasonal closures . Please research trip planning before submitting your wilderness permit application. You are limited to one application per weekly lottery window and six future reservations at any time.

Wilderness Permit Pickup: Wilderness permits must be picked up in person at a Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station the day before, or day of, your permit entry date. Wilderness permit quotas are based on the entry trailhead and entry date. If backpackers are unable to begin the trip on the entry date and at the trailhead assigned on their permit, the permit is no longer valid. As multiple trailheads may start at the same location, an entry trailhead is defined as a starting point and a direction of travel. Trip leaders are responsible for ensuring all group members are informed of wilderness regulations and the conditions of the permit.  

Late Permit Pickup: If you expect to pick up your permit after 11:00 a.m. on your entry date, login to your recreation.gov account to modify your permit reservation and mark it for late pick-up. This must be done prior to 11:00 a.m on your entry date and can only be done within one week of your entry date. If a permit is not marked for late pick up, it will be cancelled at 11am.  

Cables on Half Dome: If you're planning to hike to the top of Half Dome via the Cables as part of your wilderness itinerary, you must enter the wilderness from a Half Dome eligible trailhead. These entry trailheads are: Happy Isles->Little Yosemite Valley, Happy Isles->Past LYV (Donohue Pass Eligible), Glacier Point->Little Yosemite Valley (trailhead closed in 2022), Sunrise Lakes, Cathedral Lakes, Rafferty Creek->Vogelsang & Mono Meadow (trailhead closed in 2022). If you enter the wilderness from one of these trailheads, your entire group is eligible to go up the Half Dome Cables. Additional fees are required. You will pay for the Half Dome portion of your permit when you pick up your wilderness permit in person at a Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station .  

John Muir Trail (Donohue Pass): Due to the popularity of the John Muir Trail, a quota is in place for John Muir Trail hikers exiting Yosemite National Park over Donohue Pass. To exit Yosemite National Park over Donohue Pass, you will need to select one of the two Donohue Pass Eligible trailheads: Happy Isles->Past LYV (Donohue Pass Eligible) or Lyell Canyon (Donohue Pass Eligible). A separate Donohue Pass authorization will be issued at the same time your permit is issued.
description.no_show_policy:
If a wilderness permit is not picked up in person, or held for late arrival by 11:00 a.m. on the entry date, the reservation will be cancelled. Permits held for late arrival must be picked up at a Yosemite Wilderness Permit Station during open hours on the date of entry. There are no refunds or rebooking alternatives for permits that are not picked up. 

For specific questions, please Contact Us.
description.quota_details:
Trailhead quotas are in place to limit the number of people entering a specific trailhead each day. Quotas help to minimize human impact and provide maximum opportunity for solitude. The quota system is based on entry trailhead and entry date. Your permit is only valid if you enter the wilderness on your specified date and trailhead. Trailhead quotas are measured per person, not per permit. Of each daily trailhead quota, 60% can be reserved ahead of time, up to 24 weeks in advance.  Reservations may be made up to seven days prior to the entry date. 

The remaining 40% will be released on a first-come, first-served basis on recreation.gov seven days in advance of the start date at 7am (PDT). Popular trailheads will fill very quickly; be logged on and ready to reserve promptly at 7am (PDT) seven days in advance of your desired start date. The latest you can make a reservation is three days before a trip, subject to remaining availability.
description.season_information:
This reservation is for an overnight wilderness permit beginning in Yosemite National Park. Wilderness permits are required for all overnight backcountry use. Permits issued by Yosemite National Park are valid for continuous wilderness travel within Yosemite National Park, and adjacent wilderness areas. All permit quotas are based on entry date and entry trailhead. 

From April 29 through October 23, permit reservation requests can be made from 24 weeks to three days in advance of the start of a trip. See the Yosemite Wilderness Permits website for more information. Outside of these dates, a wilderness permit is still required and must be obtained through self-registration .  

If you wish to enter Yosemite from an adjacent wilderness area, you must obtain a wilderness permit from the agency in which your wilderness travel begins. Permits obtained from these agencies will be honored by Yosemite National Park, provided they are for continuous wilderness travel.

44585901.description:
This infrequently used trail climbs gradually through mixed conifer forest onto ridge tops above the South Fork of the Merced River. 

Alder Creek Trailhead can be accessed from two points. From either trailhead, the trail goes generally northeast toward Empire Meadows. The northern trailhead is accessed via Highway 41. The southern trailhead is accessed via Chilnualna Falls Road near Wawona.

description_map.need_to_know:
Alder Creek Trailhead can be accessed from two points. From either trailhead, the trail goes generally northeast toward Empire Meadows

You must travel at least one air mile from any road and at least four trail miles from Wawona before camping. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit
description_map.site_details: You must travel at least 1 air mile from any road & at least 4 trail miles from Wawona before camp

44585901.name: Alder Creek

44585902.description: Aspen Valley Trailhead is accessed via Aspen Valley Road off of Evergreen Road. Parking is located at the end of the road.

description_map.need_to_know:
From Aspen Valley Trailhead, you can travel south toward Tioga Road, east toward White Wolf, or north toward Smith Meadow. This trail is not used often and portions of the trail are overgrown with vegetation. Bring a good map of the area. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit

44585902.name: Aspen Valley

44585903.description: Parking for Base Line Camp Road trailhead is at the Yosemite National Park Boundary. The trailhead is accessed from Evergreen Road via Forest Service road 1S32 to 1S19. The Base Line Camp Road trail begins immediately inside the park and goes northeast toward Smith Meadow or southeast toward Aspen Valley. This trail is lightly trafficked, route finding skills are needed.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel past the Cottonwood Meadow/Aspen Valley trail junction before camping. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585903.name: Base Line Camp Road

44585904.description: This trail follows an old road as it switchbacks up the cliffs above Hetch Hetchy and then continues to ascend through the forest toward Beehive Meadow, Laurel Lake, and Lake Vernon.

description_map.need_to_know:
There is no camping allowed below the high water line of the reservoir or within four trail miles of the dam. Swimming and watering of stock directly in streams within one mile of the Reservoir is prohibited. The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco--please preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: No camping allowed below the high water line of the reservoir or within 4 trail miles of the dam.

44585904.name: Beehive Meadows

44585905.description:
This trail begins alongside Bridalveil Creek on the Glacier Point Road and heads south toward Ostrander Lake and Wawona. 

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
No camping in Bridalveil Creek Campground. If the campground is closed, you may park at McGurk Trailhead, walk the trail south of the road, then turn east into the campground and follow the campground road to Bridalveil Creek trailhead.  

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585905.name: Bridalveil Creek

44585906.description:
Budd Creek shares a starting location with the Cathedral Lakes Trailhead. You quickly leave the trail and travel cross-country up the Budd Creek Basin. 

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Budd Creek is a cross-country trailhead. There is no maintained trail along this route. Backpackers should plan accordingly. Parties cannot travel in groups larger than eight. 

Camping is prohibited in the Budd Lake and Elizabeth Lake drainages. In order to comply with wilderness regulations, your must camp south of the ridge between Echo Peaks and Cockscomb. 

Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camping is prohibited in the Budd Lake and Elizabeth Lake drainages

44585906.name: Budd Creek (cross-country only)

44585907.description:
This popular trail leads hikers into the heart of the Cathedral Range and provides various loop trip options. 

Parking for the Cathedral Lakes Trailhead is along Tioga Road on the west side of Tuolumne Meadows. The trail heads south from Tioga Road. 

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Fires are prohibited in the Cathedral Lakes Basin. Camping is prohibited in the Budd Lake and Elizabeth Lake drainages. Dispersed camping is not allowed before Upper or Lower Cathedral Lakes. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome available with this trailhead. All members of the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. Additional fees of $10 per person due when permit is issued.
description_map.site_details: No Fires  in the Cathedral Lakes Basin. No camping in Budd and Elizabeth Lake drainages

44585907.name: Cathedral Lakes

44585908.description:
After a steep hike to the top of Chilnualna Falls, visitors will enjoy the distinctive forests and lakes of the southwestern part of the park. This trail continues to Grouse, Crescent, Royal Arch, Buena Vista, and Chilnualna Lakes. 

The Chilnualna Falls trailhead can be found in the back of Wawona on Chilnualna Falls road. It travels northeast and provides access to the southern Yosemite peaks and lakes.

description_map.need_to_know:
Only use existing fire rings. Building new fire rings is not allowed. You must be at the top of Chilnualna Falls before camping. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.  

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: You must be at the top or above Chilnualna Falls before camping

44585908.name: Chilnualna Falls

44585909.description: Cottonwood Creek trailhead is just inside the Hetch Hetchy entrance station. Keep right at the first trail junction to stay on the Cottonwood Meadow Trail.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel past the Cottonwood Meadow/Aspen Valley trail junction in order to find camping. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.  

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

44585909.name: Cottonwood Creek

44585910.description:
This old railroad, old fire road, now a trail, takes hikers to Deer Camp, an old California Conservation Corps camp, and to many other secluded destinations in southern Yosemite. 

Deer Camp trailhead is just south of Glacier Point Road and the turnoff to Chinquapin. The trail goes east from the road toward Empire Meadows.

description_map.need_to_know:
Deer Camp trailhead is just south of Glacier Point Road and the turnoff to Chinquapin. The trail goes east from the road toward Empire Meadows. You must be at least one air mile from any road before you can make camp. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.  

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585910.name: Deer Camp

44585911.description:
Gaylor Creek/Lakes Trailhead can be found 2.5 miles east of the Tuolumne Wilderness Center. You will follow the trail to Lower Gaylor Lakes and then travel cross country beyond it. 

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
To use this trailhead, you must travel outside of Yosemite to find camping. No camping in park from Great Sierra Mine to White Mountain. No camping in Monroe Research Area. You may travel past Conness and back into Yosemite, or north towards allowable Forest Service camping areas. 

This is a cross-country trailhead. Beyond Gaylor Lakes, there is no maintained trail along this route. Backpackers should plan accordingly. Parties cannot travel in groups larger than eight. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: No camping in park from Great Sierra Mine to White Mountain, nor Monroe Research Area.

44585911.name: Gaylor Creek/Lake (cross-country only)

44585912.description:
Glaicer Point to Illilouette begins at Glacier Point and travels southeast towards the Illilouette Basin to destinations in the south end of the park and beyond.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel as far as the Buena Vista Trail junction before camping. You may not camp in Little Yosemite Valley on your first night with this permit. Camping is not allowed along the Panorama Trail or at the top of Illilouette Fall. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.
description_map.site_details: You must travel to the Buena Vista Trail junction before camping. No camping in LYV on night one.

44585912.name: Glacier Point->Illilouette

44585913.description:
Though slightly longer than starting from Yosemite Valley, this is an easier and very scenic hike along the Panorama Trail to Little Yosemite Valley.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.

You must spend your first night at the established backpacker sites in Little Yosemite Valley. No dispersed camping in the LYV area. Bear boxes and composting toilets are available at the campground. Fires are only permitted in the established communal fire rings. Bears have obtained food from backpackers in this area. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome available with this trailhead. All members of the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. Additional fees of $10 per person due when permit is issued.
description_map.site_details: No Donohue Pass/JMT. First night must be in LYV- use established toilets, fire rings and bear boxes

44585913.name: Glacier Point->Little Yosemite Valley

44585914.description:
This trail follows the Tuolumne River to Glen Aulin High Sierra Camp. Backpackers can then day hike to the many waterfalls along the Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne River downstream.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must camp at the established backpacker sites at Glen Aulin High Sierra Camp your first night. Bears are active and have obtained food from backpackers in this area. Fires are only permitted in the established communal fire rings. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: You must camp at the established backpacker sites at Glen Aulin High Sierra Camp your first night

44585914.name: Glen Aulin

44585915.description:
This trail follows the Tuolumne River to Glen Aulin and beyond to the Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne River, up Cold Canyon into the northern region of the park, or towards May Lake and Ten Lakes.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You may not camp at the backpacker sites at Glen Aulin High Sierra Camp on your first night. Bears are active and have obtained food from backpackers in this area. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: You may not camp at the backpacker sites at Glen Aulin High Sierra Camp on your first night.

44585915.name: Glen Aulin->Cold Canyon/Waterwheel (pass through)

44585916.description: This route follows the John Muir/Mist Trail to the top of Nevada Fall and then traverses Panorama Cliff toward Illilouette Creek.

description_map.need_to_know:
Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.

You may not camp at Little Yosemite Valley your first night. Backpackers must make it to Illilouette Basin before finding allowable camping. Camping is not allowed along the Panorama Trail or at the top of Illilouette Fall. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: You must be in Illilouette Basin before finding allowable camping. No camping at LYV on night one.

44585916.name: Happy Isles->Illilouette (No Donohue Pass)

44585917.description: This very popular trail climbs past Vernal Fall and Nevada Fall to Little Yosemite Valley and is commonly used to continue on to walk up Half Dome.

description_map.need_to_know:
Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.

You must spend your first night at the backpacker sites in Little Yosemite Valley. No dispersed camping in the LYV area. Bear boxes and composting toilets are available at the campground. Fires are only permitted in the established communal fire rings. Bears have obtained food from backpackers in this area. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is available with this trailhead. All members on the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. An additional fee of $10 per person is due when permit is issued.
description_map.site_details: No Donohue Pass/JMT. First night must be in LYV- use established toilets, fire rings and bear boxes

44585917.name: Happy Isles->Little Yosemite Valley (No Donohue Pass)

44585918.description: This very popular trail climbs past waterfalls to Little Yosemite Valley and is the start of the John Muir Trail. Continuing beyond Little Yosemite Valley brings hikers into the high country.

description_map.need_to_know:
You may not camp at Little Yosemite Valley. You must travel up the Merced River to beyond Moraine Dome or up Sunrise Creek beyond the Half Dome turn off. Bears have obtained food from backpackers in this area. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome available with this trailhead. All members of the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. Additional fees of $10 per person due when permit is issued.

Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is available for this trailhead, but not required. All members of your permit are eligible to hike over Donohue Pass. Donohue Pass will be added to your permit when it is issued.
description_map.site_details: No camping at LYV your first night. Travel at least 1 mile up Merced River or Sunrise Creek to camp.

44585918.name: Happy Isles->Past LYV (Donohue Pass Eligible)

44585919.description:
After passing by scenic Lukens Lake, this trail accesses the Middle Fork of the Tuolumne River.

The Lukens Lake Parking Lot can be found west of Yosemite Creek along Tioga Road. 

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Camping is not permitted at Lukens Lake. You must camp at least two and one-half miles from the trailhead, traveling up the Middle Tuolumne River for at least .3 miles. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camping is not permitted at Lukens Lake.

44585919.name: Luken->Lukens Lake

44585920.description:
This trail descends through the forest to the slick granite Yosemite Creek watershed.

The Lukens Lake Parking Lot can be found west of Yosemite Creek along Tioga Road.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least two miles south before finding allowable camping. Camp at least one-half mile back from the rim of the Valley. The area around the top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp at least 1/2 mile back from the valley rim, area at top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only

44585920.name: Lukens Lake->Yosemite Creek

44585921.description:
This trail meanders through Lyell Canyon along the Lyell Fork of the Tuolumne River towards Donohue Pass to the south and to Ireland Lake and Tuolumne Pass to the west.

Lyell Canyon parking is at the Tuolumne Wilderness Center or the Dog Lake parking lot. The trailhead starts near the Tuolumne Lodge parking lot.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.

Travel at least four and one-half miles out Lyell Canyon before camping. Bears have been successful at obtaining food from backpackers in this area. Fires are prohibited above 9,600 feet. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: No JMT/PCT. Travel at least 4 miles out Lyell Canyon before camping.

44585921.name: Lyell (No Donohue Pass)

44585922.description:
This trail provides access to the extremely popular John Muir Trail and other locations south.

The Lyell Canyon parking can be found at the Tuolumne Wilderness Center or the Dog Lake Parking lot. The trailhead starts near the Tuolumne Lodge Parking lot. 

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Travel at least four miles out Lyell Canyon before camping. Bears have been successful at obtaining food from backpackers in this area. No fires above 9,600 feet. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is available for this trailhead, but not required. All members of your permit are eligible to hike over Donohue Pass. Donohue Pass will be added to your permit when it is issued.
description_map.site_details: Donohue Pass Eligible. Tavel at least 4 miles out Lyell Canyon before camping.

44585922.name: Lyell Canyon (Donohue Pass Eligible)

44585923.description: This trail wanders through forest, brush, and meadows to Smith Peak.

description_map.need_to_know:
Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585923.name: Mather Ranger Station

44585924.description:
A short hike leads to scenic May Lake nestled below Mount Hoffmann, the rough geographic center of Yosemite National Park.

The May Lake trailhead parking lot is roughly two miles from the turn off on Tioga Road along the single lane Old Tioga Road. This road may open after the Tioga Road opens. This road is paved but rough. It is advised to drive slowly.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
If camping within one mile of May Lake, you must camp at the May Lake High Sierra Camp Backpackers Campground. There are bear boxes available in the area. Only use existing fire rings. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: If camping within one mile of May Lake, you must camp at HSC Backpackers Campground.

44585924.name: May Lake

44585925.description:
This is the shortest route between the Tioga Road and Yosemite Valley, taking hikers down the Snow Creek drainage to the Valley rim.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel south of Tioga Road at least one air mile before finding allowable camping. Area closure in effect near Snow Creek footbridge. You must camp north of the switchbacks and outside of the closure area to the south and east of the Snow Creek footbridge. Bears are active in this area. Do not place your bear canister near a cliff. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Travel south of Tioga Rd at least 1 air mile before camp. Camp closure near Snow Creek footbridge.

44585925.name: May Lake->Snow Creek

44585926.description:
This trail provides a relaxing hike to the southern rim of Yosemite Valley. The trailhead for McGurk Meadow is just before Bridalveil Creek Campgound the north side of Glacier Point Road

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must be four trail miles from Glacier Point before camping. Camping is prohibited east of Bridalveil Creek. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camping prohibited east of Bridalveil Creek.

44585926.name: McGurk Meadow

44585927.description: This trail follows the Beehive Meadow and Lake Vernon trail to the top of the switchbacks and then turns west through forested terrain to Miguel Meadow and Lake Eleanor.

description_map.need_to_know:
Swimming and watering of stock directly in streams within one mile of the reservoir is prohibited. The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco--please preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Swimming and watering of stock directly in streams within one mile of the reservoir is prohibited.

44585927.name: Miguel Meadow

44585928.description: The steepest climb out of the Valley, this trail takes hikers toward Snow Creek, North Dome, and the north rim of the Valley.

description_map.need_to_know:
Area closure in effect near Snow Creek footbridge. You must camp north of the switchbacks and outside of the closure area to the south and east of the Snow Creek footbridge. Bears are active in this area. Do not place your bear canister near a cliff. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Wildlife area closure: camp north of the switchbacks and south and east of the Snow Creek footbridge

44585928.name: Mirror Lake->Snow Creek

44585929.description:
From Glacier Point Road, the Mono Meadow trail provides access to the Illilouette drainage and beyond to the Panorama Trail or Clark Range.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least to the intersection of the Mono Meadow trail and the Buena Vista Trail before finding allowable camping. You must camp in Illilouette Basin or south of it on your first night. You may not camp in Little Yosemite Valley on your first night. Please keep in mind that campsites should be made on durable surfaces. 

Half Dome available with this trailhead. All members of the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. Additional fees of $10 per person due when permit is issued.

Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.
description_map.site_details: You must camp in Illilouette Basin or south on night one. No LYV on night one.

44585929.name: Mono Meadow

44585930.description:
This trail climbs through alpine meadows toward Mono and Parker Passes and Spillway Lake. Trails continue into the Ansel Adams Wilderness toward Mammoth Lakes and beyond. Backpackers must cross into the Ansel Adams Wilderness before camping.

Mono/Parker pass trailhead is on the south side of Tioga Road approximately two miles from the Tioga Pass entrance station. Mono and Parker Passes share the same trailhead as well as share the first 3.5 miles of trail before splitting from each other.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
For both Mono and Parker Passes, the permit holders must be outside of the Yosemite National Park Boundary, or outside of the Parker Creek watershed before looking for a suitable location to camp. Spillway and Helen Lakes are both part of the camping restrictions. Once the Yosemite National Park Boundary is crossed, permitted hikers are subject to the restrictions and guidelines of Inyo National Forest. Forest Service restrictions may differ from National Park Service restrictions.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp must be beyond Yosemite boundary. Forest service restrictions apply.

44585930.name: Mono/Parker Pass

44585931.description:
This trail follows Murphy Creek, then crosses open granite slabs and wanders through Lodgepole forests to Polly Dome Lakes, May Lake, or Glen Aulin.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least one air mile from Tioga Pass Road and one and half miles from the trailhead before camping. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.  

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: You must travel at least one air mile from Tioga Pass Road before camping

44585931.name: Murphy Creek

44585932.description:
This cross country route starts along the Elizabeth Lake trail and then continues over the crest between the Tuolumne and Merced River drainages, deep into the heart of the Cathedral Range.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
For 2022: Access this trailhead via the JMT to the north of Tuolumne Meadows campground. There is no parking or direct access in the Tuolumne Campground during construction. 

Fires are prohibited at Nelson and Reyman Lakes. Camping is prohibited at Elizabeth Lake. Bears are active in this area. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Fires are prohibited at Nelson and Reyman Lakes. Camping is prohibited at Elizabeth Lake.

44585932.name: Nelson Lake (cross-country only)

44585933.description: Starting from Big Oak Flat Road, his trail passes through the area burned in the 1990 fires toward Tamarack and Cascade Creeks and is often used to access the top of El Capitan. It continues east along the north rim of Yosemite Valley.

description_map.need_to_know:
Camp at least one-half mile back from the rim of the Valley. The area around the top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp at least 1/2 mile from the rim of the Valley, the area at top of Yosemite Falls is day use only

44585933.name: Old Big Oak Flat Road

44585934.description:
This is the most direct trail to Ostrander Lake, which lies nestled in a cliff lined basin. Starting from Glacier Point Road, the trail continues south toward Lost Bear Meadow.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must hike at least one air mile south of Glacier Point Road and one and half miles from the trailhead before camping. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585934.name: Ostrander (Lost Bear Meadow)

44585935.description:
This trail travels west along the south rim of the Valley, leading to beautiful vistas, such as Sentinel Dome, Taft Point, Dewey Point, and Inspiration Point.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must be four trail miles from Glacier Point before camping. Camping is not allowed east of the Bridalveil Creek footbridge. Including Taft Point.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585935.name: Pohono Trail (Glacier Point)

44585936.description:
Starting from the Taft Point trailhead along Glacier Point Road, the trail continues west along the Pohono Trail toward Bridalveil Creek.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must be four trail miles from Glacier Point before camping. Camping is not allowed east of the Bridalveil Creek footbridge including Taft Point.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585936.name: Pohono Trail (Taft Point)

44585937.description: Starting from Wawona Road at Tunnel View this trail provides hikers access to the southern rim of the Valley with destinations like Bridalveil Creek and Taft Point.

description_map.need_to_know:
Camping is not allowed east of the Bridalveil Creek footbridge.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camping is not allowed east of the Bridalveil Creek footbridge.

44585937.name: Pohono Trail (Wawona Tunnel/Bridalveil Parking)

44585938.description:
This trail provides quick access to the Tuolumne River descending 1,200 feet below O’Shaughnessy Dam.

There is no access to other trails from this route.

description_map.need_to_know:
The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. Please follow Leave No Trace outdoor ethics and help protect Yosemite Wilderness.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water

44585938.name: Poopenaut Valley

44585939.description:
Backpackers can readily access the north rim of Yosemite Valley and North Dome with its amazing vistas from this trail.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Bears are active in this area. Do not place your bear canister near a cliff.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585939.name: Porcupine Creek

44585940.description:
This trail follows the Lyell Fork of the Tuolumne River through sub-alpine meadows and then climbs along Rafferty Creek to Tuolumne Pass, Vogelsang, and destinations beyond.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Travel at least four miles from Tuolumne Meadows before finding allowable camping. There is no longer a toilet at the backpacker sites at Vogelsang. If staying at backpacker sites near Fletcher Lake, please disperse several hundred feet from the campground boundary when going to the bathroom. Fires are prohibited in the Vogelsang area, at Boothe Lake, and above 9,600 feet. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. 

Half Dome available with this trailhead. All members of the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. Additional fees of $10 per person due when permit is issued.
description_map.site_details: No bathroom at Vogelsang HSC BP, disperse 200ft to dispose human waste.

44585940.name: Rafferty Creek->Vogelsang

44585941.description:
This popular trail follows the contour of the cliffs above Hetch Hetchy Reservoir. Backpackers can continue toward Rancheria Falls and the canyons of the northwest region of the park.

Trailhead parking is available one-half mile south of the dam next to the backpackers' campground.

description_map.need_to_know:
Travel at least as far as the Tiltill Creek bridge before finding allowable camping. Swimming and watering of stock directly in streams within one mile of the reservoir is prohibited. Closure includes Wapama Falls and Rancheria Cascade. Bears active in Rancheria area. The Tuolumne River is water source for San Francisco--please preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp only past Tiltill Creek bridge. No swimming or direct watering stock within 1 mile of reservoir

44585941.name: Rancheria Falls

44585942.description: Rockslides starts from on the north side of Yosemite Valley and goes west. This is a cross country route and there is no maintained trail.

description_map.need_to_know:
Rockslides is a cross-country trailhead. There is no maintained trail along this route. Backpackers should plan accordingly. Parties cannot travel in groups larger than eight.

You must travel at least 4 trail miles from Yosemite Valley and be 1 air mile from any road before making camp. Camp at least one-half mile back from the rim of the Valley. The area around the top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp at least 1/2 mile from rim of the Valley. The area at the top of Yosemite Falls is day use only

44585942.name: Rockslides (cross-country only)

44585943.description: This seldom used trail winds up through brush and meadows to the top of Smith Peak. Although this trail is shorter than the trail leaving from Mather, there is more elevation gain.

description_map.need_to_know:
Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

44585943.name: Smith Peak

44585944.description:
This trail winds through old burn areas and mixed conifer forest and can sometimes be difficult to follow because it sees very little traffic.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.

The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585944.name: South Fork of Tuolumne River

44585945.description:
This very popular trail departs from western Tenaya Lake and follows switchbacks up toward Sunrise Lakes or Clouds Rest. Visitors can choose from several different loop options in this area such as Merced Lake, Half Dome, or Cathedral Lakes.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Hiking over Donohue Pass and hiking the JMT is NOT available for this trailhead. You will need to select one of the Donohue Pass eligible trailheads if you wish to hike the JMT.

Bears have successfully obtained food from backpackers in this area on a regular basis. Store all food and toiletries in a bear canister. Camp at least 100 feet from any water source. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome available with this trailhead. All members of the permit are eligible to walk up Half Dome. Additional fees of $10 per person due when permit is issued.

44585945.name: Sunrise (No Donohue Pass)

44585946.description:
This trail provides access to the north rim of Yosemite Valley with pleasant hiking through mixed conifer forest.

The Tamarack Creek trail can be accessed from two points. From either trailhead, the trail goes southeast from Tioga Road toward El Capitan and the north rim of Yosemite Valley."

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least to the Cascade Creek footbridge before making camp. Camp at least one-half mile back from the rim of the Valley. The area around the top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only.

Access this trailhead from Tioga Rd where there are bear boxes available.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp:  Cascade Creek footbridge and beyond,  and at least one-half mile back from the rim.

44585946.name: Tamarack Creek

44585947.description:
Provides the most direct route to Grant Lakes and the Ten Lakes basin. Hikers will pass through Half Moon Meadow and climb a ridge with rewarding views of the Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne River and Yosemite’s north country.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Fires are not allowed above 9600 feet and are permitted only in existing fire rings below that elevation. Bears are active in this area. The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

You must be at least one air mile from any road before making camp.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585947.name: Ten Lakes

44585948.description:
The Westfall Meadow trail starts just before the Bridalveil Creek Campground, passes through Westfall Meadow and goes south toward Empire Meadows.

Glacier Point Road is closed during winter and typically opens in mid May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must be at least one air mile from Glacier Point Road and one and half miles from the trailhead before camping.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585948.name: Westfall Meadow

44585949.description:
Starting from White Wolf Campground, this is a pleasant trail through red fir forest with access to different lake basins and the Yosemite Creek watershed.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least three miles before camping your first night. You cannot camp along the trails toward Aspen Valley, Smith Meadow, or Pate Valley on your first night. Camping is not allowed at Lukens Lake.

The Tuolumne River watershed is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. 

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: No camping: Lukens Lake nor the trails toward Aspen Valley, Smith Meadow, or Pate Valley on night 1.

44585949.name: White Wolf Campground

44585950.description:
The White Wolf->Aspen Valley trail starts from White Wolf and goes southwest to Aspen Valley.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
This trail is not used often and portions of the trail are overgrown with vegetation. Bring a good map of the area. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

You must travel at least as far the trail junction before Morrison Creek before camping your first night. You cannot camp along the trails toward Pate Valley, Smith Meadow, or Ten lakes on your first night.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: This trail is not used often and areas are overgrown with vegetation. Bring a good map.

44585950.name: White Wolf->Aspen Valley

44585951.description:
This trail descends into Pate Valley and gives backpackers access to the Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne River and to the trails leading into the heart of the high country.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Bears are active in Pate Valley. The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water. 

You must travel at least as far the trail junction before Morrison Creek before camping your first night. You cannot camp along the trails toward Aspen Valley, Smith Meadow, or Ten Lakes on your first night.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: You must travel at least as far the trail junction before Morrison Creek before night 1 camp.

44585951.name: White Wolf->Pate Valley

44585952.description:
The White Wolf->Smith Meadow (including Harden Lake) trail starts from White Wolf and goes northwest past Harden Lake toward Smith Meadow. 

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least as far Harden Lake before camping your first night. You cannot camp along the trails toward Aspen Valley, Pate Valley, or Ten Lakes on your first night.

This trail is not used often and portions of the trail are overgrown with vegetation. Bring a good map of the area. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585952.name: White Wolf->Smith Meadow (including Harden Lake)

44585953.description:
This beautiful path mostly follows Yosemite Creek to the Valley rim and Yosemite Falls.

The Yosemite Creek Trail can be accessed from two points, along the Tioga Road or from Yosemite Creek Campground (when open). From either trailhead, the trail goes south from Tioga Road toward the north rim of Yosemite Valley.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Your first night's camp location must be north of Yosemite Valley and south of Tioga Road. You must be at least one air mile from any road and four trail miles from Yosemite Valley before making camp. Camp at least one-half mile back from the rim of the Valley. The area around the top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only. Camping is not permitted at or near the top of Yosemite Falls, at Yosemite Point, or on North Dome.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camp at least 1/2 mile back from the valley rim, area at top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only

44585953.name: Yosemite Creek

44585954.description:
This route is a very strenuous hike up switchbacks to the top of the falls, the north rim of the Valley, and beyond.

The Yosemite Falls Trail begins in Yosemite Valley and climbs up the north rim of the valley, gaining over 2500 feet of elevation in approx. 3.5 miles. The trail continues west toward El Capitan, north toward Tioga Road, and east toward North Dome.

description_map.need_to_know:
Your first night's camp location must be north of Yosemite Valley and south of Tioga Road. You must be at least one air mile from any road and four trail miles from Yosemite Valley before making camp. Camp at least one-half mile back from the rim of the Valley. The area around the top of Yosemite Falls is for day use only. Camping is not permitted at or near the top of Yosemite Falls, at Yosemite Point, or on North Dome.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
description_map.site_details: Camping is not permitted at or near the top of Yosemite Falls, at Yosemite Point, or on North Dome.

44585954.name: Yosemite Falls

44585955.description:
Hikers along this trail enjoy forests and high meadows with panoramic views of the Cathedral Range ending at the picturesque Young Lakes.

The Young Lakes via Dog Lake Trail begins at the trail for Lembert Dome and Dog Lake before continuing north to Young Lakes.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
You must travel at least 4 trail miles from Tuolumne Meadows in order to make camp. Campfires are prohibited at Young Lakes and anywhere above 9,600 feet. The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.

44585955.name: Young Lakes via Dog Lake

44585956.description:
Hikers along this trail travel through Tuolumne Meadows to Soda Springs and follow the Glen Aulin trail for a short while before ascending through lodgepole forest toward Ragged Peak and Young Lakes.

The Young Lakes via Glen Aulin Trail follows the first 1.5 miles of the Glen Aulin Trail before diverging northward to Young Lakes.

Tioga Road is closed during winter and typically opens in late May, but can open earlier or later depending on snowpack. If you make a reservation and the road is closed, your permit is not valid and there is no refund.

description_map.need_to_know:
Campfires are prohibited at Young Lakes and anywhere above 9,600 feet. The Tuolumne River is a water source for San Francisco. Follow Leave No Trace camping techniques to preserve water quality. Along the Tuolumne Watershed, ensure all washing and waste is 300' from water.

Half Dome is NOT available with this trailhead. If you want to walk up Half Dome during your hike, you will need to get a separate day use Cables on Half Dome Permit.
